04122nam a22006375i 9781442682153DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192005onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426821537 a10.3138/97814426821532doi  a(DE-B1597)497038  a(OCoLC)1083619741  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aD16.25b.W75 2005 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a907/.2/0712221 aWright, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Professionalization of History in English Canada /cDonald Wright. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. History as avocation -- tCHAPTER 2. From avocation to vocation: the beginnings -- tCHAPTER 3. ‘The post-1918 generation’: professionalization continued -- tCHAPTER 4. ‘Mr. Newman, manifestly, is not a historian’: the amateurization of history -- tCHAPTER 5. The importance of being sexist: the masculinization of history -- tCHAPTER 6. Protecting scholarly independence: a professional imperative -- tCHAPTER 7. ‘History cannot be too much professionalized’: professionalization reconsidered -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study of history in Canada has a history of its own, and its development as an academic discipline is a multifaceted one. The Professionalization of History in English Canada charts the transition of the study of history from a leisurely pastime to that of a full-blown academic career for university-trained scholars - from the mid-nineteenth to the late twentieth century.Donald Wright argues that professionalization was not, in fact, a benign process, nor was it inevitable. It was deliberate. Within two generations, historians saw the creation of a professional association - the Canadian Historical Association - and rise of an academic journal - the Canadian Historical Review. Professionalization was also gendered. In an effort to raise the status of the profession and protect the academic labour market for men, male historians made a concerted effort to exclude women from the academy.History's professionalization is best understood as a transition from one way of organizing intellectual life to another. What came before professionalization was not necessarily inferior, but rather, a different perspective of history. As well, Wright argues convincingly that professionalization inadvertently led to a popular inverse: the amateur historian, whose work is often more widely received and appreciated by the general public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHistoriographyzCanadaxHistory. 0aHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher)zCanadaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268215340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682153423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682153.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK